hr viel mehr der griechischen Komödie folgen, als verschiedentlich angenommen wurde.  aTo what extent is Roman comedy dependent on the Greek? The author pursues this old controversy using a comprehensive study of the figure of the Parasite. The Parasite, stemming from the Greek socio-historical context and at first an alien phenomenon for Roman society, itself reflects the historical literary relationship of Roman comedy (located in a Greek milieu) to its Attic precursors. By investigating the development of the figure of the Parasite on the Roman stage, Andrea Antonsen-Resch gains new insights into the degree to which the relevant plays are dependent on Greek models. One result is to demonstrate that Plautus and Terence follow Greek comedy to a far greater extent than has often been thought.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aRömische Komödie. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAntonsen-Resch, A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2005z9783110277111oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET ALTERTUM 2005z9783110276985oZDB-23-DGD0 cprintz978311018167840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311091262340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110912623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110912623/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2005  aZDB-23-DGGb2005  aZDB-23-GCNc2000d2014